De Klerk said he would sue to block the long-awaited final report of the Truth and Reconciliation Commission, which was due for release Thursday. The commission found her accountable for human rights violations committed by her bodyguards, who the report said killed and tortured suspected opponents. Madikizela-Mandela was convicted in 1991 of kidnapping and being an accessory to an assault on four young men. She was sentenced to six years in jail, but paid a dlrs 3,200 fine on appeal. The ANC official was among the most prominent anti-apartheid activists. The two generals were implicated during Truth Commission testimony. Prosecutors are ready to move forward pending the amnesty application of one. 